    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="207"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d207">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EAC/11–1444</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Conversation, by the Under Secretary of
                        State</hi> (<hi rend="italic">Stettinius</hi>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-14">November 14,
                            1944</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <table>
                    <row>
                        <cell rendition="#top #nowrap">Present:</cell>
                        <cell rendition="#hanging">Major General Hilldring, Civil Affairs Division,
                            War Department; Colonel Cutter, War Department; Mr. Matthews—EUR;<note
                                n="75" xml:id="d207fn1">Office of European Affairs.</note> Mr.
                                Hamilton—SA/HA;<note n="76" xml:id="d207fn2">Maxwell M. Hamilton,
                                Special Assistant to the Secretary of State.</note> Mr.
                                Leverich—CE;<note n="77" xml:id="d207fn3">Henry P. Leverich,
                                Assistant Chief, Division of Central European Affairs.</note> Mr.
                                Lynch—U<note n="78" xml:id="d207fn4">Robert J. Lynch, Special
                                Assistant to the Under Secretary of State.</note>
                        </cell>
                    </row>
                </table>
                <p>Mr. McCloy called on the Under Secretary this morning to discuss a letter to Mr.
                    Stettinius from Lord Halifax dated November 10. The letter suggested that our
                    interim directive for the treatment of Germany (JCS 1067)<note n="78a"
                        xml:id="d207fn5">See bracketed note, <ref target="#pg_341">p.
                        341</ref>.</note> be circulated to EAC.</p>
                <p>It was agreed to do this after the paper had been changed to make it tripartite
                    in nature rather than a directive addressed only to SCAEF.</p>
                <pb facs="0421" n="407" xml:id="pg_407"/>
                <p>Mr. McCloy said that he would make the necessary alterations in the paper and
                    would send us a copy for ultimate transmission to Ambassador Winant.</p>
            </div>
